  "prompt": "Has modern medicine and technology eliminated Natural Selection in humans?",
  "response": "While modern medicine and technology have significantly reduced the impact of natural selection, they have not completely eliminated it. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Reduced mortality\n- Medical advances have reduced infant and child mortality\n- Treatments for previously fatal diseases have increased survival rates\n- People with genetic conditions can now live longer and reproduce\n\n2. Ongoing selective pressures\n- Genetic resistance to diseases\n- Environmental adaptations\n- Sexual selection still occurs\n- Genetic variations still impact reproductive success\n\n3. Continuing genetic variations\n- Not all medical interventions can prevent genetic disorders\n- Some genetic traits still influence survival and reproduction\n- Complex interactions between genes and environment continue\n\n4. Technological impacts\n- Reproductive technologies allow people with genetic conditions to have children\n- Genetic screening can reduce certain inherited diseases\n- Artificial selection through genetic choices is emerging\n\n5. Complex evolutionary dynamics\n- Natural selection is still occurring, but at a slower and different pace\n- Human populations continue to adapt to changing environments\n- Genetic diversity remains important for species survival\n\nWhile modern medicine has dramatically altered natural selection's traditional mechanisms, it has not completely eliminated evolutionary processes in humans.",
